Polinom derecesinin seÃ§iminde klasik ANOVA yaklaÅŸÄ±mÄ±: polinom modeller birbirlerinin iÃ§inde yuvalanmÄ±ÅŸ parametrelerde doÄŸrusal modellerdir. Bu nedenle standart F testiyle modelleri sÄ±nayabiliriz. Bunun iÃ§in anova() fonksiyonunu kullanabiliriz.

fit.1 <- lm(wage ~ age, data=Wage)
fit.2 <- lm(wage ~ poly(age,2),data=Wage)
fit.3 <- lm(wage ~ poly(age,3),data=Wage)
fit.4 <- lm(wage ~ poly(age,4),data=Wage)
fit.5 <- lm(wage ~ poly(age,5),data=Wage)
anova(fit.1, fit.2, fit.3, fit.4, fit.5)

Polinom terimli lojistik regresyon modeli:

fit <- glm( I(wage>250) ~ poly(age, 4), data=Wage, family=binomial)
preds <- predict(fit, newdata=list(age=age.grid), se=T)

# obtain standard error bands 
pfit <- exp(preds$fit)/(1+exp(preds$fit))
se.bands.logit <- cbind(preds$fit+2*preds$se.fit, preds$fit-2*preds$se.fit)
se.bands <- exp(se.bands.logit)/(1+exp(se.bands.logit))

2 Spline Regresyonu

Râ€™da {splines} kÃ¼tÃ¼phanesini kullanarak spline regresyonu kurabiliriz. Baz fonksiyonlarÄ±nÄ±n oluÅŸturulmasÄ±nda bs() fonksiyonu kullanÄ±labilir (default = cubic). Ã–rneÄŸin,

library(splines)
fit <- lm(wage ~ bs(age, knots=c(25,40,60)), data=Wage)
pred <- predict(fit, newdata=list(age=age.grid), se=T)
plot(Wage$age, Wage$wage, col="gray", 
     xlab = "Age", ylab = "Wage")
lines(age.grid, pred$fit, lwd=2)
lines(age.grid, pred$fit+2*pred$se, lty="dashed")
lines(age.grid, pred$fit-2*pred$se, lty="dashed")
abline(v=c(25,40,60), lty=2, col="darkgreen")

DÃ¼ÄŸÃ¼m noktalarÄ±: age = 25, 40, 60. Toplamda 6 baz fonksiyonu oluÅŸturuldu. 3 dÃ¼ÄŸÃ¼m noktalÄ± bir kÃ¼bik spline toplamda 7 serbestlik derecesine sahiptir (=3+3+1).

Alternatif olarak df() fonksiyonu ile uniform aralÄ±klar kullanarak dÃ¼ÄŸÃ¼m noktalarÄ±nÄ± belirleyebiliriz.

dim(bs(Wage$age, knots=c(25,40,60)))
## [1] 3000    6
dim(bs(Wage$age, df=6))
## [1] 3000    6
attr(bs(Wage$age, df=6), "knots")
##   25%   50%   75% 
## 33.75 42.00 51.00

Burada R dÃ¼ÄŸÃ¼m noktalarÄ±nÄ± 33.8, 42.0, ve 51.0 deÄŸerlerinde oluÅŸturdu. Bu deÄŸerler, sÄ±rasÄ±yla, 25, 50 ve 75nci yÃ¼zdelik dilimlerdir (1,2,3. kartiller).

2.2 Smoothing Splines

Bunun iÃ§in stats::smooth.spline() fonksiyonu kullanÄ±labilir:

plot(Wage$age, Wage$wage, xlim = agelims, cex = 0.5, col="darkgrey", 
     xlab = "Age", ylab = "Wage")
title(" Smoothing Spline ")
# fit a smoothing spline with degree 16
fit <- smooth.spline(Wage$age, Wage$wage, df = 16)
# chose df using cross-validation
fit2 <- smooth.spline(Wage$age, Wage$wage, cv = TRUE)
# cv yields df=6.8
fit2$df
## [1] 6.794596
lines(fit, col="red",lwd=2)
lines(fit2, col="blue",lwd=2)
legend("topright",legend=c("16 DF","6.8 DF"),col=c("red","blue"),lty=1,lwd=2,cex=.8)

2.3 Ã–rnek: simÃ¼lasyon verileriyle spline regresyonu

Ã–nce veri setimizi oluÅŸturalÄ±m:

# simulate data
set.seed(12345)
n  <- 100
x  <- seq(0,1,length=n)
fx <- 5*x*sin(2*pi*x) + 4*cos(3*pi*x)
y  <- rnorm(n,fx,1)
data = data.frame(y,x)

Verilerin grafiÄŸi:

library(ggplot2)
p1 <- ggplot(data,aes(x,y)) +
       geom_point() 
  
p1 + geom_line(aes(x,fx,col="Truth")) +
  scale_colour_manual(" ", values=c("Truth"="black"))

Ä°ki dÃ¼ÄŸÃ¼m noktasÄ± tanÄ±mlayalÄ±m:

# we have  knots 
k1 <- 0.33
k2 <- 0.62 
p1 + geom_line(aes(x,fx,col="Truth")) +
     scale_colour_manual(" ", values=c("Truth"="black")) +
     geom_vline(xintercept=c(k1,k2), 
                linetype="dotted", color = "blue", size=1)

data$k1dummy <- ifelse(data$x>k1,1,0)
data$k1diff <- data$x - k1
data$xk1 <- data$k1diff*data$k1dummy
#
data$k2dummy <- ifelse(data$x>k2,1,0)
data$k2diff <- data$x - k2
data$xk2 <- data$k2diff*data$k2dummy
ggplot(data, aes(x,xk1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_line(aes(x,xk2,col="red")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

bs() fonksiyonu ile gÃ¶rselleÅŸtirme:

library(splines)

matplot(x,B,type="l",lty=1,lwd=2)

Ä°kinci derece spline:

3 Yerel Regresyon

Bu amaÃ§la stats::loess() fonksiyonu kullanÄ±labilir. Detaylar iÃ§in bkz. ?loess. (loess: locally estimated scatterplot smoothing ya da LOcal regrESSion, aka lowess: locally weighted scatterplot smoothing).

plot(Wage$age, Wage$wage, xlim = agelims, cex = 0.5, col="darkgrey", 
     xlab = "Age", ylab = "Wage")
title("Local Regression")
fit <- loess(wage ~ age, span=0.2, data=Wage)
fit2 <- loess(wage ~ age, span=0.5, data=Wage)
lines(age.grid, predict(fit, data.frame(age=age.grid)), col="red", lwd=2)
lines(age.grid, predict(fit2, data.frame(age=age.grid)), col="blue", lwd=2)
legend("topright", legend=c("Span=0.2","Span=0.5"), 
       col=c("red","blue"), lty=1, lwd=2, cex=.8)

Yerel regresyonda tahminde kullanÄ±lan yerel verileri span deÄŸeri belirler. YukarÄ±da iki deÄŸer kullanÄ±lmÄ±ÅŸtÄ±r: 0.2 ve 0.5, sÄ±rasÄ±yla verilerin %20â€™si ve %50â€™si dahil edilmiÅŸtir. Span deÄŸeri bÃ¼yÃ¼dÃ¼kÃ§e tahmin edilen eÄŸri dÃ¼zleÅŸir. Yerel regresyonun tahmininde alternatif olarak {locfit} kÃ¼tÃ¼phanesi de kullanÄ±labilir.

Ã–rnek: SimÃ¼lasyon verileri ile yerel regresyon:

library(tidyverse)
data_fit <- loess(y ~ x, span = 0.1, data = data)
y_hat <- predict(data_fit, data$x)
data_fit2 <- loess(y ~ x, span = 0.3, data = data)
y_hat2 <- predict(data_fit2, data$x)
df <- tibble(y = data$y, 
             x = data$x, 
             pred = y_hat,
             pred2 = y_hat2)
head(df)
## # A tibble: 6 Ã— 4
##       y      x  pred pred2
##   <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  4.59 0       4.75  4.31
## 2  4.69 0.0101  4.34  4.18
## 3  3.83 0.0202  3.97  4.03
## 4  3.41 0.0303  3.66  3.88
## 5  4.37 0.0404  3.46  3.72
## 6  1.82 0.0505  3.31  3.56
ggplot(df, aes(x,y)) + geom_point() + 
  geom_line(aes(x,fx,col="Truth")) +
  geom_line(aes(x,pred, col="Span=0.1")) + 
  geom_line(aes(x,pred2, col="Span=0.3"))

ggplot2::geom_smooth() ile LOESS:

ggplot(data, aes(x,y)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(aes(x,fx,col="Truth")) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", span=0.1, se = FALSE, aes(col="span=0.1")) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", span=0.3, se = FALSE, aes(col="span=0.3"))

Åžimdi simÃ¼lasyon ile oluÅŸturduÄŸumuz veri setinden hareketle train-test ayÄ±rÄ±mÄ± yapalÄ±m. Bundan Ã¶nce, deÄŸiÅŸkenleri 0-1 aralÄ±ÄŸÄ±na olacak ÅŸekilde standardize edelim:

scale1 <- function(x){
  (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x))
}
dfs <- df %>% mutate_all(scale1)
# %75 train %25 test
set.seed(555)
train_id <- sample(1000, 750)
dfs_train <- dfs[train_id, ]
dfs_test <- dfs[-train_id, ]
# 1 hÃ¼creli tek katman, default act.fct = "logistic" (i.e., sigmoid)
nnet1 <- neuralnet(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data=dfs_train)
plot(nnet1, rep = "best")

# 2 hÃ¼creli tek katman
nnet2 <- neuralnet(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data=dfs_train, hidden=2)
plot(nnet2, rep = "best")

# 3 hÃ¼creli tek katman
nnet3 <- neuralnet(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data=dfs_train, hidden=3)
plot(nnet3, rep = "best")

# 3 hÃ¼creli 2 katman
# relu <- function(x) {max(0,x)}
nnet4 <- neuralnet(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data=dfs_train, hidden=c(3,3))
plot(nnet4, rep = "best")

library(tidyverse)
library(MASS)
library(neuralnet)
data("Boston")
# scale variables, except chas and medv
# boston <- as_tibble(Boston) %>% 
#  mutate(across(.cols=-c("chas","medv"), scale1))
boston <- as_tibble(Boston) %>% 
  mutate(across(.cols=-c("chas"), scale1))
# scale1 fonksiyonu yukarÄ±da tanÄ±mlanmÄ±ÅŸtÄ±
# train-test split

set.seed(10) # for replication
boston_split <- initial_split(boston, 
                           prop = 0.75, 
                           strata = medv)
# train-test verileri
boston_train <- boston_split %>% training()
boston_test <- boston_split %>% testing()
# iki saklÄ± katman, herbirinde 5 nÃ¶ron
set.seed(1010)
nn1 <- neuralnet(medv ~ crim + zn + indus + chas + nox + rm + age + dis + rad + tax + 
                   ptratio + black + lstat,
                 data = boston_train,
                 hidden = c(5,5))
# YSA'nÄ±n yapÄ±sÄ± 
plot(nn1, col.hidden = 'darkgreen',     
     col.hidden.synapse = 'darkgreen',
     show.weights = F,
     information = F,
     fill = 'lightblue', 
     rep = "best"   # to render graph in html output
     )

# kestirimler
pred_nn1 <- predict(nn1, newdata = boston_test)

# scale1'i tersine Ã§evir
pred_nn1_converted <- (max(pred_nn1)-min(pred_nn1))*pred_nn1 + min(pred_nn1)
test_medv <- (max(boston_test$medv)-min(boston_test$medv))*boston_test$medv + min(boston_test$medv)
# tibble oluÅŸtur
result_data <- tibble(test_medv, pred_nn1_converted)
head(result_data)
## # A tibble: 6 Ã— 2
##   test_medv pred_nn1_converted[,1]
##       <dbl>                  <dbl>
## 1     0.369                  0.444
## 2     0.398                  0.417
## 3     0.256                  0.336
## 4     0.222                  0.460
## 5     0.309                  0.401
## 6     0.293                  0.367
# MSE hesapla
mse_boston_nn1 <- mean((pred_nn1_converted - test_medv)^2)
mse_boston_nn1
## [1] 0.01119983
# tÃ¼m deÄŸiÅŸkenlerle lineer regresyon 
reg1 <- lm(medv ~ crim + zn + indus + chas + nox + rm + age + dis + rad + tax + 
                   ptratio + black + lstat, data = boston_train)
pred_reg1 <- predict(reg1, newdata = boston_test)
pred_reg1_converted <- (max(pred_reg1)-min(pred_reg1))*pred_reg1 + min(pred_reg1)
result_data$pred_reg1_converted <- pred_reg1_converted
head(result_data)
## # A tibble: 6 Ã— 3

## 4     0.222                  0.460              0.117 
## 5     0.309                  0.401              0.180 
## 6     0.293                  0.367              0.119
# lineer regresyon MSE deÄŸeri 
mse_boston_reg1 <- mean((pred_reg1_converted - test_medv)^2)
mse_boston_reg1
## [1] 0.04876404
# Kestirim karÅŸÄ±laÅŸtÄ±rmasÄ±

  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("YSA(5,5)")
p2 <- ggplot(result_data, aes(test_medv, pred_reg1_converted)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Lineer Regresyon")
